class domopt.Point(x, f)¶

Object for storing designs in optimization. It can be called as a tuple, corresponding to (x, f)

Parameters:
  • x (list) – Object representing the design that the optimization manipulates, i.e. scaled design variables
  • f (object) – Object that measures performance, it must have the < and == operators defined.
class domopt.Stochastic(design=None, samples=None, criteria='MV')¶

Represents an design’s performance through stochastic samples

Parameters:
  • design (list) – list of design variables determining the design
  • samples (list) – list of samples of the quantity of interest evaluated at the given design variables
  • criteria (str) – dominance criteria to use to compare the performance of different designs. It can be a string (one of ‘mv’, ‘zsd’, ‘fsd’, ‘ssd’) or a list of strings of these types.
FSDcompare(design, other)¶

Compares two designs for first order stochastic dominance using the empirical quantile function for comparison.

MVcompare(design, other)¶

Compares designs using Pareto dominance using the sample mean and standard deviation

SSDcompare(design, other)¶

Compares two designs for first order stochastic dominance using the empirical superquantile function for comparison.

ZSDcompare(design, other)¶

Compares two designs for zeroth order stochastic dominance using the minimum and maximum of the samples.

class domopt.Optimization(evaluator, bounds, observer=None)¶

Base class for optimziations operating on Point objects.

Designs are stored as Point objects - the first entry is what the optimizer controls (i.e. scaled design variables), the second entry is an object provided obtained by the evaluator method that measures performance, it must have a comparison operator.

This generalization allows any comparison operator to be defined and thus general non-dominance criteria to be used.

The optimizer scales the design variables to range over [0,10] so that an algorithm’s methods operate over an appropriate scaled space.

Parameters:
  • evaluator (function) – Function that takes a vector of design variables and returns an object that can be compared via < and == operators.
  • bounds (list) – List of bounds on design variables in the form [(l0, u0), (l1, u1), ..., (ln, un)] where lb, uk are the lower and upper bounds on the kth design variable respectively.
  • observer (function) – User defined function that is called every time a Point is evaluated, it is passed the current Point, the current non-dominated archive, and the list of all points visited. It should be able to be called by myObserver(point, archive, history)
class domopt.PolySurrogate(dimensions, order=3, poly_type='legendre')¶

Class for creating surrogate models using non-intrusive polynomial chaos.

Parameters:
  • dimensions (int) – number of dimensions of the polynomial expansion
  • order (int) – order of the polynomial expansion [default 3]
  • poly_type (str/list) – string of the type of polynomials to use in the expansion, or list of strings where each entry in the list is the type of polynomial to use in the corresponding dimension. Supported polynomial types are legendre and gaussian. [default legendre]

Example Declaration:

>>> thePC = PolySurrogate(dimensions=3)
>>> thePC = PolySurrogate(dimensions=3, order=3)
>>> thePC = PolySurrogate(dimensions=3, order=3, poly_type='legendre')
getQuadraturePoints()¶

Gets the quadrature points at which the output values must be found in order to train the polynomial expansion using gaussian quadrature.

Returns:upoints - a np.ndarray of size (num_polynomials, num_dimensions)
Return type:np.ndarray
getQuadraturePointsAndWeights()¶

Gets the quadrature points and weights for gaussian quadrature integration of inner products from the definition of the polynomials in each dimension.

Returns:(u_points, w_points) - np.ndarray of shape (num_polynomials, num_dimensions) and a np.ndarray of size (num_polynomials)
Return type:(np.ndarray, np.ndarray)
predict(u)¶

Predicts the output value at u from the fitted polynomial expansion. Therefore the method train() must be called first.

Parameters:u (numpy.ndarray) – input value at which to predict the output.
Returns:q_approx - the predicted value of the output at u
Return type:float

Sample Usage:

>>> thePC = PolySurrogate(dimensions=2)
>>> U = thePC.getQuadraturePoints()
>>> Q = [myFunc(u) for u in U]
>>> thePC.train(U, Q)
>>> thePC.predict([0, 1])
surrogate(u_sparse, q_sparse)¶

Combines the train and predict methods to create a surrogate model function fitted to the input/output combinations given in u_sparse and q_sparse.

Parameters:
  • u_sparse (numpy.ndarray) – input values at which the output values are obtained. Must be the same as the qaudrature points defined by the getQuadraturePoints method.
  • q_sparse (numpy.ndarray) – output values corresponding to the input values given in u_sparse to which the surrogate is fitted
Returns:

surrogate model fitted to u_sparse and q_sparse
Return type:

function

Sample Usage:

>>> thePC = PolySurrogate(dimensions=2)
>>> U = thePC.getQuadraturePoints()
>>> Q = [myFunc(u) for u in U]
>>> surrogateFunc = thePC.surrogate(U, Q)
train(ftrain)¶

Trains the polynomial expansion.

Parameters:ftrain (numpy.ndarray/function) – output values corresponding to the quadrature points given by the getQuadraturePoints method to which the expansion should be trained. Or a function that should be evaluated at the quadrature points to give these output values.

Sample Usage:

>>> thePC = PolySurrogate(dimensions=2)
>>> thePC.train(myFunc)
>>> predicted_q = thePC.predict([0, 1])

>>> thePC = PolySurrogate(dimensions=2)
>>> U = thePC.getQuadraturePoints()
>>> Q = [myFunc(u) for u in U]
>>> thePC.train(Q)
>>> predicted_q = thePC.predict([0, 1])
